default&#xa0;default(ii)default defaultCentre for Excellence and Outcomes (C4EO) defaultresearch reviewdefault24. 
defaultIn 2011, the 
defaultCentre for Excellence and Outcomes published a research review on ‘
defaultEffective classroom strategies for closing the gap in educational achievement for children and young people living in poverty, including white working-class boys
default’
default.
default defaultThe report sought to exa
defaultmine what 
defaultworks in closing the gap in educational achievement for children and young people living in poverty, including white working-class boys. 
defaultIt identified that that schools are adopting a number of promising strategies to improve outcomes for 
defaultchildren living in poverty including:
default25. 
defaultThe report also highlighted
default the valuable contribution that 
defaultthe sector can play in
default improving 
defaultthe attainment and achievement of children and young people from disadvantaged backgrounds:
default 
default26.
default defaultChildrdefaulten and young peopledefault living in poverty respond to classroom interventions that improve instructional processes and teaching methods. Well-specified and well-supported programmes and practices provide the greatest learning outcomes, which motivate and engage
default all learners, not just those from poor backgrounds. Children from deprived areas respond positively to opportunities that raise their aspirations for learning and future success. 
default27.
default defaultParents and carersdefault should be actively engaged by schools to support th
defaulteir child’s development and learning. Breaking cycles of low aspiration and disenfranchisement with education is an important step for narrowing attainment gaps. 
default&#xa0;
default28.
default defaultStrong and visionary leadershipdefault, provided by head teachers and principals, is often the 
defaultdriving force behind improving outcomes for children living in poverty. Senior decision-makers play a key role in improving teaching strategies, by providing extensive professional development in evidence-based programmes and practices. 
default&#xa0;
default29. 
defaultAs the direct
default contact point with pupils in schools, 
defaulteducation staffdefault are the key route to inspiring children from low-income families into learning. They need to develop their teaching methods to meet the needs of these young people in line with evidence-based strategies drawn from the profession and research. 
default&#xa0;
default30.
default defaultLocal defaultauthoritiesdefault need to work across the Early Years Foundation Stage sector, primary and secondary schools to support the adoption of evidence-based programmes and practices in schools. They should encourage changes in pedagogy through extensive, school-based 
defaultprofessional development. They should plan targeted approaches to raise the aspirations of children from low-income families and engage parents in school life. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn a climate of financial austerity it is crucial that schools target any new resources for po
defaultor children into interventions that are proven to raise outcomes. 
defaultNational policy-makersdefault should support the use of evidence-based strategies and interventions, and build more widespread access to programmes of this kind.
